<DOC><DOCNO> AP901220-0165 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-12-20-90 2047EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Major     12-20 0154</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bush-Major,140</SECOND><HEAD>British Prime Minister Arrives</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   New British Prime Minister John Major arrivedhere Thursday night for discussions with U.S. officials.   Major, prime minister only three weeks, arrived in a Royal AirForce transport at Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington.   He is scheduled to visit congressional leaders and Secretary ofState James A. Baker III on Friday before flying by helicopter withBush to Camp David in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains, thepresidential retreat.   Bush and Major will have a joint news conference on Saturday.   Like his predecessor Margaret Thatcher, Major has pledgedwholehearted support for the U.S. military buildup in the PersianGulf. Britain is sending 21,000 troops.   It has become traditional for new British prime ministers tovisit the White House soon after assuming office. Major has visitedthe United States three times before as chancellor of theexchequer.</TEXT></DOC>